SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 827
By Walley
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Emmett L. Bolyard of
Bolivar.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Emmett L. Bolyard of
Bolivar; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Bolyard was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Bolyard was born on February 1, 1939, in Columbiana, Ohio, and
moved to Tennessee in 1963; as a young man, he served in the U.S. Army Reserve; and
WHEREAS, Emmett Bolyard joined the Bolivar Fire Department on January 1, 1964,
beginning what would become an extraordinary legacy of commitment and sacrifice; and
WHEREAS, he was later hired as a career firefighter, becoming the first paid firefighter
within Bolivar; he was promoted to captain in 1970 and assistant chief in 1994, roles he filled
with integrity, humility, and devotion; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Bolyard received the coveted Firefighter of the Year Award once in
1982 and again in 2002; he provided unwavering service until 2001, when he reached his
mandatory retirement age of sixty-two, but he remained an active volunteer firefighter until 2025;
and
WHEREAS, in total, Emmett Bolyard gave selflessly to the Bolivar community for more
than sixty-one years as a firefighter; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his firefighting career, Mr. Bolyard served as a reserve school
bus driver for Hardeman County Schools, helped run the ambulance service in Hardeman
County, and worked at the Jervis Corporation; and
SJR0827
013302
- 1 -

WHEREAS, a man of deep faith, Emmett Bolyard was an active member of Bolivar's
First Methodist Church, where he served as custodian for over fifteen years; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Bolyard was also deeply devoted to his family, and he took great pride
in caring for them, always remaining true to family values of the highest order; he cherished time
spent with his grandchildren and was always there to support them in their sporting endeavors;
and
WHEREAS, beyond spending time with his family, Emmett Bolyard enjoyed the simple
pleasures in life, including watching The Young and the Restless; and
WHEREAS, he will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by his two sons, William
"B.J." (Becky) Bolyard and Craig Bolyard; grandchildren, Shelby Bolyard Parker, Alyssa
Bolyard, Lindy Bolyard, Kadea Bolyard, Abby Bolyard Ruble, Cody Bolyard, Austin Bolyard,
Tanner Parker, Tucker Parker, and Abbie Parker; great-grandchildren, Jackson Jewell Bolyard,
Emma Lee Bolyard, Nash Allen Bolyard, Harper Grace Ruble, Maverick Ross Parker, and
MacKenzie Blake Parker; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Bolyard was preceded in death by his beloved wife, Patricia Bowers
Bolyard; daughter, Linda Bolyard Evans; father, Truman P. Bolyard; mother, Thelma Grace
Kurtz Bolyard; and daughter-in-law, Sherelle Bolyard; and
WHEREAS, Emmett Bolyard leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we should remember the bountiful life of this exceptional
public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Emmett L. Bolyard,
- 2 - 013302

reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Bolyard.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
